<br>
- well my thought on that was from beta (yes I played beta)<br>
<br>
<br>
As a gaming company, you have a product, you want to sell this product, but there is already a large MMORG already developed with a large player base. How do I break into that market?<br>
<br>
 - did they infact leave out the rules to push for a larger following?<br>
 - should they now enforce a EULA now that they have a large player base?<br>
 - is it because someone is making money off their developed product?<br>
 - did they investigate/probe into the problems of other MMORGs have gone through with the EBay Market, and chose to ignore it to draw more of a crowd?<br>
<br>
My thoughts (IMO) are and I don't have a legal degree, but I do know something about business - the problem was known, and ignored for the purpose of sales of the original release, the company is now trying to put a "stop" to it so it doesn't ruin the reputation of the game (further sales and releases, + newer content to draw more customers, IE: What are we missing that people want and not getting in other games? What don't they like? What keeps them here longer, if they can just go out and buy (real money) items, characters etc, and resell them, the game will get boring and they will leave).<br>
<br>
Why was the problem ignored?<br>
  - takes time for people to get to a point of the game to be able to start actual making a profit.  <br>
 - Take EQ for example, same thing occured; IE: UO had some of the same problems, again the problem was known. Difference was; no law suit; or the unknowns were squashed or paid off to STFU.<br>
<br>
Should Mythic have to pay for this?<br>
 - quite frankly I would have to agree with those 7 people sitting in that room making cash.<br>
 - why? well it all comes down to this, business is what ever you make of it if you are not violating the law (IE: thats why we have lawyers). <br>
 - In the end do I feel big business will win out? quite possibly, but really depends on those 7 guys sitting in that room. "Do they have anything to lose?" and "Will the law support thier claims?"<br>
<br>
The truth is, tho I don't agree with EBaying, its America folks, and its American Laws, and to the pursuit of happiness I hope they actual win.<br>
<br>
